04970nam a22009255i 9780814759592DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20102010nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147595927 a10.18574/nyu/9780814795989.001.00012doi  a(DE-B1597)548096  a(OCoLC)779828200  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPS374.R32bM87 2016 7aLIT0040402bisacsh04a813.40935522231 aMurphy, Gretchen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aShadowing the White Man’s Burden :bU.S. Imperialism and the Problem of the Color Line /cGretchen Murphy. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAmerica and the Long 19th Century ;v2400tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. Reading Kipling in America -- t1. The Burden of Whiteness -- t2. The White Man’s Burden or the Leopard’s Spots? -- tPart II. The Black Cosmopolite -- t3. The Plain Citizen of Black Orientalism -- t4. Pauline Hopkins’s “International Policy” -- tPart III. Pacific Expansion and Transnational Fictions of Race -- t5. How the Irish Became Japanese -- t6. American Indians, Asiatics, and Anglo-Saxons -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDuring the height of 19th century imperialism, Rudyard Kipling published his famous poem “The White Man’s Burden.” While some of his American readers argued that the poem served as justification for imperialist practices, others saw Kipling’s satirical talents at work and read it as condemnation. Gretchen Murphy explores this tension embedded in the notion of the white man’s burden to create a new historical frame for understanding race and literature in America.Shadowing the White Man’s Burden maintains that literature symptomized and channeled anxiety about the racial components of the U.S. world mission, while also providing a potentially powerful medium for multiethnic authors interested in redrawing global color lines. Through a range of archival materials from literary reviews to diplomatic records to ethnological treatises, Murphy identifies a common theme in the writings of African-, Asian- and Native-American authors who exploited anxiety about race and national identity through narratives about a multiracial U.S. empire. Shadowing the White Man’s Burden situates American literature in the context of broader race relations, and provides a compelling analysis of the way in which literature came to define and shape racial attitudes for the next century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAmerican fictiony19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aImperialism in literature. 0aRace in literature. 0aRacism in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / African-American.2bisacsh  aAmerica.  aGretchen.  aMurphy.  aburden.  acreate.  aembedded.  aexplores.  aframe.  ahistorical.  aliterature.  amans.  anotion.  arace.  atension.  athis.  aunderstanding.  awhite.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081479598940uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814795989.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814759592423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814759592/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  